                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I refuse to sign the petition until the superfulous apostrophe is removed from the thread title.
<br />

<br />
Actually I read the petition, and I won't sign it.  Apparently the petition is in support of a bill that would automatically suspend for sixth months any commercial driver's license (CDL) if the CDL holder is involved in a fatal accident, and mandate 100 hours of community service before the CDL is reinstated.  The only exception to this rule would be if the person who died as a result of the accident caused the accident.
<br />

<br />
What's missing from the law is the requirement that the person who loses his or her license (and livelihood, most likely) for sixth months have himself or herself caused the accident.
<br />

<br />
Imagine an accident that involves just two  drivers.  CDL holder is going through an intersection with a green light.  Driver runs a red light on the intersecting street and broadsides the CDL holder.  Driver has Passenger in his car.  Driver suffers serious injuries, and Passenger dies.  CDL holder loses his license for six months, under the proposed statute at the linked petition.
<br />

<br />
That's an idiotic law, and runs contrary to fundamental principles of criminal responsibility.  Strict liability for merely being involved (as opposed to negligently, recklessly, or intentionally causing) a fatal accident makes absolutely no sense whatsoever.  I hope that bill NEVER passes.  It's absurd and unworthy of a decent society.
<br />

<br />
The collision and death that gave rise to this petition is heartbreaking, and I hope that the driver is ultimately held accountable.  However, everyone should stop and think before they throw their support behind a law to "fix" what appears to be an unjust situation.  I would like to read the report of the investigating officer.  I would like to have many more facts than the reader is given at that petition in order to understand what apparently happened.  
<br />

<br />
We should hesitate before we rush to assign criminal responsibility for every bad act or unjust event we see.  Besides, the legal system is there for a reason.  The civil justice system--what's left of it given the current political climate, at least--exists precisely to remedy wrongs like that poor woman's death.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=646635" target="_blank" class="postlink">Saediien Iluvatri</a>
<br />
Retired Coercer of The Rathe
<br />
Saed - Mage - Windrunner - &lt;Dazed&gt;
<br />
Saediien - Druid - Stormrage - &lt;Guardians of Paradise&gt;</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
