                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I am truly sorry for this person's loss, however, I would like to share my own story.  As a lifelong resident of the state of Illinois, I have to confess that I was once responsible for an accident not all that unsimilar to this one.  The car in front of me had stopped at a stop sign quite a ways in front of me, and for some reason I had a mental lapse and thought that this car had proceeded to turn when, in fact, it had not.  Needless to say, I rear-ended the poor soul whom was in the wrong place at the wrong time.  Now, I had driven this way many times, so I was very much aware of the stop sign at this intersection, and I had been following this car for at least 10 miles, so I knew he was there, too.  Something just went wrong with my thought process for a few minutes and I just screwed up.  Fortunately, I was already slowing down, since it was a stop sign, and all that resulted of this accident was damage to both of our cars.  And I received the same failure to stop $75 ticket.
<br />

<br />
Now, I understand in my case, nobody died (and I was even fortunate enough not to have hit one of the 99% of the American sue happy public whom would ordinarily feign a whole host of unprovable back injuries).  I also understand that I am not an employee of some sort of commercial trucking company, and I am unfamiliar with the state commercial driving regulations.  But still, what if somebody had died?  I don't feel I deserve to have lost my licence for six months, a year, forever, or, heaven forbid, even have gone to jail for causing this accident.  It was my one and only accident in six years of driving, pretty good for the average person my age.  Had I killed someone in this accident, I doubt the $75 fine would even register compared to the emotional trauma of having to live with the fact that I had done such a thing.
<br />

<br />
I did not click the link, but going by the post on this forum, I see no evidence indicating this was anything but a genuine accident.  And I guess I just want to say that driving accidents, regrettably, do ocasionally happen, and will continue to happen as long as humans continue to operate vehicles.  Driving is an inherently risky activity, and though we assign blame to the transgressor in these sort of accidents, few among you reading can claim to say they have never been the cause of an accident.  Perhaps forgiveness is a better response than revenge, especially considering this was likely truly accidental.
<br />

<br />
It seems to me the purpose of this petition is that the family of the unfortunate victim is simply not content in forgiving this driver's (regrettably big) mistake, and have decided they need to do everything in their power to try and make his life even more of a living hell than it must already be, living with the fact that he accidentally took someone's life.
<br />

<br />
If this wasn't an accident, but truly a reckless or intentional act on the part of the driver, then by all means, let's burn him at the stake!   But based on the information provided, I just see no reason to further punish this driver and will not sign this petition.
<br />

<br />
Edit - I read the link, which is a good thing, because the petiton itself leaves out the emotional details in this post that make this accident seem worse that what is appears to be - an accident.  I can't remember my own ticket, but I do know when I get parking tickets from the cops at my school (technically State of Illinois cops, not city cops), if I pay them within 10 days I can cut the fine in half.  If it applies it could clear up the issue of $75 or $150 - technically it was a $150 fine but it was payed quickly for $75.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Amerie Robeseeker, 65th level Enchantress
<br />
Amedahast Deadlink, 60th level Warrior
<br />
Level 20-40 Everything Else
<br />

<br />
On vacation after 5 long years of adventuring!
<br />

<br />
Morell Thule Server
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Beware of he that would deny you access to information,
<br />
for in his heart, he dreams himself your master.</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
