                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">It is nearly impossible that the at-fault truck driver will avoid responsibility, because resposibilty can be manifest in forms other than criminal punishment.
<br />

<br />
The fact is, a collision like the one described above translates not into an "insurance claim" (i.e., pennies on the dollar), but a big-time lawsuit.  The case is easily worth seven figures, should the survivors of the poor woman who died decided to seek a remedy in the civil justice system.  Tractor trailers are required by law to carry multi-million dollar insurance policies for exactly this reason.  I can guarantee you when the employer of the truck driver and/or its insurance comapny is eventually forced to pay out over a million dollars, there will be consequences for the employee.
<br />

<br />
Criminal negligence and civil negligence are not the same thing.  If a lawsuit is brought, the truck driver will be held to account for his negligence, and possibly the employer may be accountable, too, for entrusting the driver with a tractor-trailer if there are problems with the driver's driving record.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=646635" target="_blank" class="postlink">Saediien Iluvatri</a>
<br />
Retired Coercer of The Rathe
<br />
Saed - Mage - Windrunner - &lt;Dazed&gt;
<br />
Saediien - Druid - Stormrage - &lt;Guardians of Paradise&gt;</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
